### Configure programmatic styles in Go

Source: https://context7.com/charmbracelet/glamour/llms.txt

Build custom styles programmatically using Glamour's StyleConfig struct. Shows how to customize headers, links, and text formatting with specific colors and formatting rules. Includes uppercase headers, title case formatting, and custom link styles for advanced terminal rendering.

```go
func main() {
    // Start with a base style
    customStyle := styles.DarkStyleConfig

    // Customize specific elements
    uppercase := true
    customStyle.H1.Upper = &uppercase
    customStyle.H1.Prefix = ">>> "
    customStyle.H1.Suffix = " <<<"

    titleCase := true
    customStyle.H2.Title = &titleCase
    customStyle.H2.Prefix = "== "

    customColor := "99"
    customStyle.Link.Color = &customColor
    customStyle.Link.Format = "[{{.text}}]({{.url}})"

    // Create renderer with custom style
    renderer, err := glamour.NewTermRenderer(
        glamour.WithStyles(customStyle),
        glamour.WithWordWrap(100),
    )
    if err != nil {
        fmt.Printf("Error: %v\n", err)
        return
    }

    markdown := `# this will be uppercase
## this will be title case

Check out this [amazing link](https://example.com) with custom color!

**Bold text** and *italic text* are also styled.
`

    output, err := renderer.Render(markdown)
    if err != nil {
        fmt.Printf("Error: %v\n", err)
        return
    }

    fmt.Print(output)
}
```

--------------------------------

### Heading elements style in JSON

Source: https://github.com/charmbracelet/glamour/blob/master/styles/README.md

Example JSON configuration for heading elements (h1 to h6), including prefixes, margins, and text styling.

```json
"heading": {
    "color": "15",
    "background_color": "57"
},
"h1": {
    "prefix": "=> ",
    "suffix": " <=",
    "margin": 2,
    "bold": true,
    "background_color": "69"
},
"h2": {
    "prefix": "## ",
    "margin": 4
},
"h3": {
    "prefix": "### ",
    "margin": 6
}
```

--------------------------------

### Load custom styles from JSON file

Source: https://context7.com/charmbracelet/glamour/llms.txt

Apply custom markdown styling using external JSON configuration files. The example shows loading styles from both file paths and JSON byte arrays. Requires a valid JSON style configuration file at the specified path.

```Go
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "github.com/charmbracelet/glamour"
)

func main() {
    // Load style from JSON file
    renderer, err := glamour.NewTermRenderer(
        glamour.WithStylesFromJSONFile("./custom-style.json"),
        glamour.WithWordWrap(100),
    )
    if err != nil {
        fmt.Printf("Error loading style: %v\n", err)
        return
    }

    markdown := "# Custom Styled Markdown\n\nThis uses a **custom** JSON style."

    output, err := renderer.Render(markdown)
    if err != nil {
        fmt.Printf("Error: %v\n", err)
        return
    }
    fmt.Print(output)

    // Alternative: Load from JSON bytes
    jsonStyle := []byte(`{
        "document": {
            "color": "252",
            "margin": 2
        },
        "h1": {
            "color": "228",
            "bold": true,
            "prefix": "# "
        }
    }`)

    renderer2, err := glamour.NewTermRenderer(
        glamour.WithStylesFromJSONBytes(jsonStyle),
    )
    if err != nil {
        fmt.Printf("Error: %v\n", err)
        return
    }

    output2, err := renderer2.Render(markdown)
    if err != nil {
        fmt.Printf("Error: %v\n", err)
        return
    }
    fmt.Print(output2)
}
```

